# Java Coding Standards

## Language Baseline
- Minimum: Java 17 LTS. Recommended: Java 21 LTS.
- Use `jakarta.*` namespace exclusively; never `javax.annotation` or `javax.validation`.

## Naming
- Packages: reverse domain, all lowercase, no underscores (`com.example.ordermanagement`)
- Classes/Interfaces: PascalCase. Avoid `Impl` suffix; use descriptive names (`StripePaymentProcessor`)
- Methods/Variables: camelCase. Boolean: `is*`, `has*`, `can*`, `should*`
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE, defined in owning class
- Test classes: `*Test`, `*IntegrationTest`, `*AcceptanceTest`

## Formatting
- 4-space indentation, 120-character line limit
- No wildcard imports
- Import order: `java.*`, `jakarta.*`, third-party, project-internal, static imports last
- Files end with newline, UTF-8 encoding, no trailing whitespace

## Class Design
- One public class per file
- Group by feature/domain, not by technical layer
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Keep classes focused (Single Responsibility)
- Limit method parameters to 3-4; use parameter objects for more

## Methods
- Under 30 lines preferred
- Early returns to reduce nesting
- Avoid boolean parameters; use enums or separate methods
- Validate inputs at public boundaries with `Objects.requireNonNull`

## Null Safety
- JSpecify annotations at package level (`@NullMarked`)
- Return `Optional` for methods that may not produce a result
- Return empty collections, never `null`

## Constructor Injection
- Constructor injection only (no field or setter injection)
- Mark all dependencies `final`

